Researchers from the medical charity Doctors without Borders (MSF) said despite the stigma surrounding abortion, many South African women saw it as "just another medical procedure" necessary in some instances.

Postings by women on an MSF blog showed women felt that both practical and emotional support for women included having "a place where one goes and obtain access to the procedure as and when they want to have it eg a clinic free of judgement and threats". Others felt it was important to avoid unnecessary stress, to be able to choose whether pregnancy happened or not and "not be [screwed] over by controversial third parties who have their own train of thinking and howling at the moon".

This article is from the BBC News website. To read the rest of the piece, please follow this link http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-12595598
